SIMPLE: start
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: start
<hw>start</hw> <pr>(st⟦aum⟧rt)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>started</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>starting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sterten</ets>; akin to
D. <ets>storten</ets> to hurl, rush, fall, G. <ets>st⟦uum⟧rzen</ets>,
OHG. <ets>sturzen</ets> to turn over, to fall, Sw. <ets>st⟦oum⟧rta</ets>
to cast down, to fall, Dan. <ets>styrte</ets>, and probably also to E.
<ets>start</ets> a tail; the original sense being, perhaps, to show the
tail, to tumble over suddenly. ⟦root⟧166. Cf. <er>Start</er> a
tail.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To leap; to jump.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move suddenly, as with a spring or leap, from
surprise, pain, or other sudden feeling or emotion, or by a voluntary
act.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And maketh him out of his sleep to <qex>start</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>start</qex> as from some dreadful dream.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Keep your soul to the work when ready to <qex>start</qex>
aside.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But if he <qex>start</qex>,⟦br⟧
It is the flesh of a corrupted heart.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To set out; to commence a course, as a race or
journey; to begin; <as>as, to <ex>start</ex> in business</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At once they <qex>start</qex>, advancing in a line.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At intervals some bird from out the brakes⟦br⟧
<qex>Starts</qex> into voice a moment, then is still.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To become somewhat displaced or loosened; <as>as, a
rivet or a seam may <ex>start</ex> under strain or
pressure</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To start after</b></col>, <cd>to set out after; to
follow; to pursue.</cd> -- <col><b>To start against</b></col>, <cd>to
act as a rival candidate against.</cd> -- <col><b>To start
for</b></col>, <cd>to be a candidate for, as an office.</cd> --
<col><b>To start up</b></col>, <cd>to rise suddenly, as from a seat or
couch; to come suddenly into notice or importance.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1405 pr=VMG --></p>

<p><ent>Start</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Start
<hw>Start</hw> <pr>(st⟦aum⟧rt)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To cause to move suddenly; to disturb suddenly; to startle; to
alarm; to rouse; to cause to flee or fly; <as>as, the hounds
<ex>started</ex> a fox</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon malicious bravery dost thou come⟦br⟧
To <qex>start</qex> my quiet?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Brutus will <qex>start</qex> a spirit as soon as Caesar.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring into being or into view; to originate; to
invent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sensual men agree in the pursuit of every pleasure they can
<qex>start</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to move or act; to set going, running, or
flowing; <as>as, to <ex>start</ex> a railway train; to <ex>start</ex> a
mill; to <ex>start</ex> a stream of water; to <ex>start</ex> a rumor; to
<ex>start</ex> a business</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I was engaged in conversation upon a subject which the people love
to <qex>start</qex> in discourse.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To move suddenly from its place or position; to
displace or loosen; to dislocate; <as>as, to <ex>start</ex> a bone; the
storm <ex>started</ex> the bolts in the vessel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One, by a fall in wrestling, <qex>started</qex> the end of the
clavicle from the sternum.</q> <rj><qau>Wiseman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[Perh. from D. <ets>storten</ets>, which has this
meaning also.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To pour out; to empty; to
tap and begin drawing from; <as>as, to <ex>start</ex> a water
cask</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Start</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Start
<hw>Start</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of starting; a
sudden spring, leap, or motion, caused by surprise, fear, pain, or the
like; any sudden motion, or beginning of motion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fright awakened Arcite with a <qex>start</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A convulsive motion, twitch, or spasm; a spasmodic
effort.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For she did speak in <qex>starts</qex> distractedly.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature does nothing by <qex>starts</qex> and leaps, or in a
hurry.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sudden, unexpected movement; a sudden and
capricious impulse; a sally; <as>as, <ex>starts</ex> of
fancy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To check the <qex>starts</qex> and sallies of the soul.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The beginning, as of a journey or a course of
action; first motion from a place; act of setting out; the outset; --
opposed to <ant>finish</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>start</qex> of first performance is all.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I see you stand like greyhounds in the slips,⟦br⟧
Straining upon the <qex>start</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>At a start</b></col>, <cd>at once; in an instant.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>At a start</qex> he was betwixt them two.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To get the start</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To
have the start</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to begin before another; to gain or
have the advantage in a similar undertaking; -- usually with
<xex>of</xex>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Get the start</xex> of the majestic
world.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧She might have forsaken him if he
had not <xex>got the start</xex> of her.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Dryden.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Start</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Start
<hw>Start</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>stert</ets> a tail, AS.
<ets>steort</ets>; akin to LG. <ets>stert</ets>, <ets>steert</ets>, D.
<ets>staart</ets>, G. <ets>sterz</ets>, Icel. <ets>stertr</ets>, Dan.
<ets>stiert</ets>, Sw. <ets>stjert</ets>. ⟦root⟧166. Cf. <ets>Stark
naked</ets>, under <er>Stark</er>, <er>Start</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A tail, or anything projecting like a
tail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The handle, or tail, of a plow; also, any long
handle.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The curved or inclined front and bottom of a
water-wheel bucket.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>The arm, or lever, of a gin,
drawn around by a horse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>START</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: START
<hw>START</hw> <pr>(st⟦aum⟧rt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<ets>S</ets>trategic <ets>A</ets>rms <ets>R</ets>eduction
<ets>T</ets>reaty.]</ety> <def>A Treaty between the United States and
the Soviet Union which provided for stepwise reductions in the number of
nuclear weapons possessed by each country.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Starter</ent>⟦br⟧
